Tuesday September 8, 1998

Monsanto Sows Seeds Of Discontent In Canada, India

Multinational chemical giant Monsanto Co. is raising ire internationally with
its various campaigns to make genetically modified foods and seeds the next
big thing in agriculture, despite environmental concerns about the
ramifications of such poorly understood tampering.

In Canada, environmentalists are wary of Monsanto's plan to "give Mother
Nature a helping hand" by producing pesticide- and herbicide-resistant corn
and other crops. Critics warn that not enough is known about the side effects
of fooling with the natural engineering of crops, and are concerned that most
people eating these foods are unaware of the crops' origins, since
genetically
altered seeds are not subject to mandatory labeling.

Monsanto, apparently aware of such criticisms, has launched an extensive
"greenwashing" campaign, including a recent brochure, printed on recycled
paper with the motto "Food, Health, Hope," claiming that the new genetically
altered foods help promote sustainable development. "By working now to put
the
technology and the infrastructure required to meet future foods needs, we can
feed the world for centuries to come and improve the quality of life for
people worldwide," the brochure states.

But groups like Oxfam charge that pharmaceutical companies are merely
developing a market for their chemicals, and that herbicide-resistant seeds
could make individuals resistant to antibiotics.

Concerns are growing in Canada, where in Ontario, for example, 15 percent of
all corn production is now genetically altered. Monsanto's altered corn and
potatoes, which have been available in Canada since 1996, work by adding an
extra gene to seeds to produce insect-protected crops. Canadian farmers also
use herbicide-resistant corn, soybean and canola seeds, which allow a
plant to
flourish in the face of chemicals that kill surrounding weeds.

Monsanto's own "Roundup corn," designed to tolerate the company's Roundup
herbicide could be the next genetically modified product to hit the Canadian
market. If this corn is developed, farmers will be required, by contract, to
use only Monsanto's Roundup herbicide. The product already has obtained
one of
the two necessary safety approvals from Canadian officials, and is under
review for the second.

In India, another pending Monsanto product -- the so-called "terminator gene"
-- has raised fears, although the company insists that it does not exist. .
.yet.

The terminator gene is said to make grains sterile rendering them unfit for
use as seed. The result would be that farmers could not reuse the produce as
seed and would have to buy them from the producing company every season. 

Agricultural scientists worry that if the gene found its way into non-target
crops that results could be catastrophic, and have expressed misgivings about
foreign multinationals using advanced technology to corner India's massive
seed market. Environmentalists also have raised concerns about the protection
of biodiversity.

The controversy arose after the USDA and the Delta and Pine Land company, one
of Monsanto's seed company partners, applied for a "prophetic patent" for the
terminator gene. Monsanto claims that plans for the the gene are still in a
conceptual phase and that it does not yet exist. The idea, according to
company spokespersons, was to develop a process that would provide gene
protection to plants such as tobacco.

Sources: "Canadians Unknowingly Eat Genetically Altered Crops," Reuters,
August 26, 1998; "Monsanto says terminator gene does not exist," The Business
Standard (New Delhi edition) August 4, 1998.
