Majoring in Martians
by Kristen Philipkoski 

11:59 a.m.  2.Oct.98.PDT

We are not alone. 

And the University of Washington is likely to make first contact. This week
the Seattle-based university announced the creation of a graduate program
to train students in the search for extraterrestrial life. 

Officials say that the University of Washington is the first to offer a
doctorate in astrobiology, where students compare extreme environments on
Earth to those on other planets, such as Mars and Europa, one of Jupiter's
moons. The program will begin in the fall semester of 1999, and is funded
from a five-year, US$2 million National Science Foundation grant, plus
$500,000 from the university. 

"I think this is really exciting," said Chris Chyba, the Carl Sagan chair
for the study of life in the universe at the Search for Extraterrestrial
Intelligence Institute. "For the first time in a quarter century, the field
is returning to this question of looking for life elsewhere. We did it with
Viking in '76, and they had to look at Mars using the technology of the
early '70s. Now we’ve got 25 more years of technology." 

Graduates will be able to receive degrees in 11 areas, with an emphasis in
astrobiology. Students can choose from oceanography, astronomy, aeronautics
and astronautics, genetics, chemistry, biochemistry, microbiology,
atmospheric sciences, geophysics, geological sciences, or history as their
core focus of study. 

"What's special about it is it's a cross-disciplinary curriculum of
physical and biological sciences," said James Staley, a UW microbiology
professor and director of the astrobiology program. 

The goal of the astrobiology doctorate program, which is expected to enroll
about 12 students, is to make analogies between extreme environments on
Earth and environments on other planets, Staley said. 

"Our theme is that we'd like to study environments on earth as models of
environments that might exist in Europa or Mars," he said. "The ocean has
hydrothermal vents (like undersea volcanoes) and there is life associated
with these environments... which might be an analogue for life on Mars
beneath the surface. The sea ice at the North and South poles, which covers
10 percent of the oceans, has a microbial community of very cold-loving
organisms. We think the sea-ice community might be an analogue for life on
Europa." 

Chyba said the discovery of a deep biosphere within the Earth has rekindled
interest in searching for life on other planets. "If organisms can live a
mile down into the Earth, they may have retreated there on Mars," he said. 

Scientists have gathered circumstantial evidence of an ocean on Europa,
raising hopes of eventually discovering life there. "Exobiologically, that
would make Europa one of the most exciting places," Chyba said. 

NASA apparently agrees, since it plans to put a spacecraft in orbit above
Europa in 2003 to try and confirm the existence of an ocean. If one is
found, the moon will be extensively studied. Chyba predicts that Mars
missions will also start bearing fruit within a decade. 

"It’s no longer purely a theoretical field," Chyba said. "People have to
think hard about how to interpret and do experiments." 

Until now, students interested in exploring extraterrestrial life have had
to tailor their curriculums through conventional means. This might mean
majoring in astronomy while taking courses in molecular biology or
microbiology. 

Some schools, the University of Arizona for example, offer a PhD program in
planetary sciences, and a minor in astrobiology. And the NASA Specialized
Center of Research and Training developed a doctorate program at the
University of San Diego focusing on exobiology, which studies the origins
of life. 

Rachel Mastrapa, a PhD candidate who is pursuing a minor in astrobiology at
the University of Arizona, said she sees many graduate students interested
in astrobiology. 

"In some ways I’m the guinea pig," she said. "My success could dictate
whether or not they put a lot of money into a [major] program. I hope to
see it progress to an official major." 

For students with backgrounds in astronomy and geology, the biological
science courses can be challenging, Mastrapa said. "I’m taking a course in
organic chemistry to catch up, and next semester I’ll have to take
microbiology. But if the major works out, they could tailor the program to
people coming in from different backgrounds." 

With funding from The National Science Foundation and the cropping up of
university programs, the field of astrobiology is likely to move well
beyond studying suspicious circular formations in Iowa cornfields. 

