The US Attorneys Office, on behalf of the Army, has submitted its Motion
for Summary Judgment (dismissal) and in support of its motion it has
submitted affidavits from various personnel swearing to the adequacy and
scope of the search.

The following areas were searched without success:

1) Office of the Assistant Secretary of the Army for Research, Development
and Acquisition (SARDA) This office had taken over responsibilities for the
Office of the Chief of Research and Development (OCORD) where Corso was
assigned. In particular all SF 135s documenting SARDA record transfers for
the years 1960-1970. The search included a visual and physical check of the
records and files, and electronic checks of all current, historical and
archived paper and computer files maintained by SARDA Information
Management Office, as well as historical files transferred to storage.

2) Army Medical Command (MEDCOM) and Office of Surgeon General (OTSG) A
search was conducted of all their current and historical paper and
electronic records, reasonable or remote.

3) Intelligence and Security Command (INSCOM) A search was conducted of all
their current and historical paper and electronic records, reasonable or
remote. Though no records were found responsive to the CAUS request, CAUS
did receive a large amount documents from INSCOM pertaining to WWII era
German flying wing aircraft which were, according to the Army, 'perceived
as UFOs or flying saucers.'

The US Attorneys Office maintains that the Army has performed a 'reasonable
search' which is all that the law requires.  It now asks the Court to
dismiss the CAUS lawsuit.  The lawsuit will be dismissed unless I can argue
that the Army's search was either in bad faith or unreasonable under the
circumstances. The law is also clear that only a 'reasonable' search is
required...not an 'exhaustive' search and the mere fact that documents
might have existed at one time is not evidence that they exist at the
present time.

Since Colonel Corso is no longer alive to assist CAUS with its response,
CAUS is seeking member guidance as whether there are other areas within the
Army that should have been searched for responsive documents.  Any such
recommendation must be supported by some arguable reason to believe that
the documents would be found there.  Prior to the Colonel's death, he had
informed me that on several occasions he had personally attempted to have
the Army locate his files but without success.

